The metal ions exhibit particularly mobile properties within the interstices of CsSnBr3. Our previous results17 revealed that the Sn vacancy is of high concentration in CsSnBr3. One may envisage that the metal ions may penetrate CsSnBr3 along the interstice, and then fill the Sn vacancies to form substitutional impurities in the bulk of the active layer. To support this hypothesis, we calculated the energy barriers for these processes, and the results are summarized in Fig. 6. In this case, the energy barrier is the diffusion barrier for the action that an interstitial metal ion Mi+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
